[SCENE.\'97A room furnished comfortably and tastefully, but not extravagantly. At the back, a door to the right leads to the entrance-hall, another to the left leads to Helmer\'92s study. Between the doors stands a piano. In the middle of the left-hand wall is a door, and beyond it a window. Near the window are a round table, arm-chairs and a small sofa. In the right-hand wall, at the farther end, another door; and on the same side, nearer the footlights, a stove, two easy chairs and a rocking-chair; between the stove and the door, a small table. Engravings on the walls; a cabinet with china and other small objects; a small book-case with well-bound books. The floors are carpeted, and a fire burns in the stove. It is winter.
\f1\i0 \

\f0\i A bell rings in the hall; shortly afterwards the door is heard to open. Enter NORA, humming a tune and in high spirits. She is in outdoor dress and carries a number of parcels; these she lays on the table to the right. She leaves the outer door open after her, and through it is seen a PORTER who is carrying a Christmas Tree and a basket, which he gives to the MAID who has opened the door.]
\f1\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 NORA.\uc0\u8232 Hide the Christmas Tree carefully, Helen. Be sure the children do not see it until this evening, when it is dressed. 
\f0\i [To the PORTER, taking out her purse.]
\f1\i0  How much?\
PORTER.\uc0\u8232 Sixpence.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 There is a shilling. No, keep the change. 
\f0\i [The PORTER thanks her, and goes out. NORA shuts the door. She is laughing to herself, as she takes off her hat and coat. She takes a packet of macaroons from her pocket and eats one or two; then goes cautiously to her husband\'92s door and listens.]
\f1\i0  Yes, he is in. 
\f0\i [Still humming, she goes to the table on the right.]
\f1\i0 \
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [calls out from his room]
\f1\i0 . Is that my little lark twittering out there?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [busy opening some of the parcels]
\f1\i0 . Yes, it is!\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Is it my little squirrel bustling about?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes!\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 When did my squirrel come home?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Just now. 
\f0\i [Puts the bag of macaroons into her pocket and wipes her mouth.]
\f1\i0  Come in here, Torvald, and see what I have bought.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Don\'92t disturb me. 
\f0\i [A little later, he opens the door and looks into the room, pen in hand.]
\f1\i0  Bought, did you say? All these things? Has my little spendthrift been wasting money again?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes but, Torvald, this year we really can let ourselves go a little. This is the first Christmas that we have not needed to economise.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Still, you know, we can\'92t spend money recklessly.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, Torvald, we may be a wee bit more reckless now, mayn\'92t we? Just a tiny wee bit! You are going to have a big salary and earn lots and lots of money.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Yes, after the New Year; but then it will be a whole quarter before the salary is due.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Pooh! we can borrow until then.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Nora! 
\f0\i [Goes up to her and takes her playfully by the ear.]
\f1\i0  The same little featherhead! Suppose, now, that I borrowed fifty pounds today, and you spent it all in the Christmas week, and then on New Year\'92s Eve a slate fell on my head and killed me, and\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [putting her hands over his mouth]
\f1\i0 . Oh! don\'92t say such horrid things.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Still, suppose that happened,\'97what then?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 If that were to happen, I don\'92t suppose I should care whether I owed money or not.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Yes, but what about the people who had lent it?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 They? Who would bother about them? I should not know who they were.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 That is like a woman! But seriously, Nora, you know what I think about that. No debt, no borrowing. There can be no freedom or beauty about a home life that depends on borrowing and debt. We two have kept bravely on the straight road so far, and we will go on the same way for the short time longer that there need be any struggle.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [moving towards the stove]
\f1\i0 . As you please, Torvald.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [following her]
\f1\i0 . Come, come, my little skylark must not droop her wings. What is this! Is my little squirrel out of temper? 
\f0\i [Taking out his purse.]
\f1\i0  Nora, what do you think I have got here?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [turning round quickly]
\f1\i0 . Money!\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 There you are. 
\f0\i [Gives her some money.]
\f1\i0  Do you think I don\'92t know what a lot is wanted for housekeeping at Christmas-time?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [counting]
\f1\i0 . Ten shillings\'97a pound\'97two pounds! Thank you, thank you, Torvald; that will keep me going for a long time.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Indeed it must.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, yes, it will. But come here and let me show you what I have bought. And all so cheap! Look, here is a new suit for Ivar, and a sword; and a horse and a trumpet for Bob; and a doll and dolly\'92s bedstead for Emmy,\'97they are very plain, but anyway she will soon break them in pieces. And here are dress-lengths and handkerchiefs for the maids; old Anne ought really to have something better.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 And what is in this parcel?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [crying out]
\f1\i0 . No, no! you mustn\'92t see that until this evening.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Very well. But now tell me, you extravagant little person, what would you like for yourself?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 For myself? Oh, I am sure I don\'92t want anything.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Yes, but you must. Tell me something reasonable that you would particularly like to have.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, I really can\'92t think of anything\'97unless, Torvald\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Well?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [playing with his coat buttons, and without raising her eyes to his]
\f1\i0 . If you really want to give me something, you might\'97you might\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Well, out with it!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [speaking quickly]
\f1\i0 . You might give me money, Torvald. Only just as much as you can afford; and then one of these days I will buy something with it.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 But, Nora\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Oh, do! dear Torvald; please, please do! Then I will wrap it up in beautiful gilt paper and hang it on the Christmas Tree. Wouldn\'92t that be fun?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 What are little people called that are always wasting money?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Spendthrifts\'97I know. Let us do as you suggest, Torvald, and then I shall have time to think what I am most in want of. That is a very sensible plan, isn\'92t it?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [smiling]
\f1\i0 . Indeed it is\'97that is to say, if you were really to save out of the money I give you, and then really buy something for yourself. But if you spend it all on the housekeeping and any number of unnecessary things, then I merely have to pay up again.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Oh but, Torvald\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 You can\'92t deny it, my dear little Nora. 
\f0\i [Puts his arm round her waist.]
\f1\i0  It\'92s a sweet little spendthrift, but she uses up a deal of money. One would hardly believe how expensive such little persons are!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 It\'92s a shame to say that. I do really save all I can.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [laughing]
\f1\i0 . That\'92s very true,\'97all you can. But you can\'92t save anything!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [smiling quietly and happily]
\f1\i0 . You haven\'92t any idea how many expenses we skylarks and squirrels have, Torvald.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 You are an odd little soul. Very like your father. You always find some new way of wheedling money out of me, and, as soon as you have got it, it seems to melt in your hands. You never know where it has gone. Still, one must take you as you are. It is in the blood; for indeed it is true that you can inherit these things, Nora.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Ah, I wish I had inherited many of papa\'92s qualities.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 And I would not wish you to be anything but just what you are, my sweet little skylark. But, do you know, it strikes me that you are looking rather\'97what shall I say\'97rather uneasy today?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Do I?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 You do, really. Look straight at me.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [looks at him]
\f1\i0 . Well?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [wagging his finger at her]
\f1\i0 . Hasn\'92t Miss Sweet Tooth been breaking rules in town today?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No; what makes you think that?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Hasn\'92t she paid a visit to the confectioner\'92s?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, I assure you, Torvald\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Not been nibbling sweets?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, certainly not.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Not even taken a bite at a macaroon or two?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, Torvald, I assure you really\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 There, there, of course I was only joking.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [going to the table on the right]
\f1\i0 . I should not think of going against your wishes.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 No, I am sure of that; besides, you gave me your word\'97 
\f0\i [Going up to her.]
\f1\i0  Keep your little Christmas secrets to yourself, my darling. They will all be revealed tonight when the Christmas Tree is lit, no doubt.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Did you remember to invite Doctor Rank?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 No. But there is no need; as a matter of course he will come to dinner with us. However, I will ask him when he comes in this morning. I have ordered some good wine. Nora, you can\'92t think how I am looking forward to this evening.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 So am I! And how the children will enjoy themselves, Torvald!\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 It is splendid to feel that one has a perfectly safe appointment, and a big enough income. It\'92s delightful to think of, isn\'92t it?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 It\'92s wonderful!\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Do you remember last Christmas? For a full three weeks beforehand you shut yourself up every evening until long after midnight, making ornaments for the Christmas Tree, and all the other fine things that were to be a surprise to us. It was the dullest three weeks I ever spent!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I didn\'92t find it dull.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [smiling]
\f1\i0 . But there was precious little result, Nora.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Oh, you shouldn\'92t tease me about that again. How could I help the cat\'92s going in and tearing everything to pieces?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Of course you couldn\'92t, poor little girl. You had the best of intentions to please us all, and that\'92s the main thing. But it is a good thing that our hard times are over.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, it is really wonderful.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 This time I needn\'92t sit here and be dull all alone, and you needn\'92t ruin your dear eyes and your pretty little hands\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [clapping her hands]
\f1\i0 . No, Torvald, I needn\'92t any longer, need I! It\'92s wonderfully lovely to hear you say so! 
\f0\i [Taking his arm.]
\f1\i0  Now I will tell you how I have been thinking we ought to arrange things, Torvald. As soon as Christmas is over\'97
\f0\i [A bell rings in the hall.]
\f1\i0  There\'92s the bell. 
\f0\i [She tidies the room a little.]
\f1\i0  There\'92s some one at the door. What a nuisance!\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 If it is a caller, remember I am not at home.\
MAID.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [in the doorway]
\f1\i0 . A lady to see you, ma\'92am,\'97a stranger.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Ask her to come in.\
MAID.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [to HELMER]
\f1\i0 . The doctor came at the same time, sir.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Did he go straight into my room?\
MAID.\uc0\u8232 Yes, sir.\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi320\sa80\qj\partightenfactor0

\f0\i \cf0 [HELMER goes into his room. The MAID ushers in Mrs Linde, who is in travelling dress, and shuts the door.]
\f1\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [in a dejected and timid voice]
\f1\i0 . How do you do, Nora?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [doubtfully]
\f1\i0 . How do you do\'97\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 You don\'92t recognise me, I suppose.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, I don\'92t know\'97yes, to be sure, I seem to\'97
\f0\i [Suddenly.]
\f1\i0  Yes! Christine! Is it really you?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Yes, it is I.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Christine! To think of my not recognising you! And yet how could I\'97
\f0\i [In a gentle voice.]
\f1\i0  How you have altered, Christine!\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Yes, I have indeed. In nine, ten long years\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Is it so long since we met? I suppose it is. The last eight years have been a happy time for me, I can tell you. And so now you have come into the town, and have taken this long journey in winter\'97that was plucky of you.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 I arrived by steamer this morning.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 To have some fun at Christmas-time, of course. How delightful! We will have such fun together! But take off your things. You are not cold, I hope. 
\f0\i [Helps her.]
\f1\i0  Now we will sit down by the stove, and be cosy. No, take this armchair; I will sit here in the rocking-chair. 
\f0\i [Takes her hands.]
\f1\i0  Now you look like your old self again; it was only the first moment\'97You are a little paler, Christine, and perhaps a little thinner.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 And much, much older, Nora.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Perhaps a little older; very, very little; certainly not much. 
\f0\i [Stops suddenly and speaks seriously.]
\f1\i0  What a thoughtless creature I am, chattering away like this. My poor, dear Christine, do forgive me.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 What do you mean, Nora?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [gently]
\f1\i0 . Poor Christine, you are a widow.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Yes; it is three years ago now.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, I knew; I saw it in the papers. I assure you, Christine, I meant ever so often to write to you at the time, but I always put it off and something always prevented me.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 I quite understand, dear.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 It was very bad of me, Christine. Poor thing, how you must have suffered. And he left you nothing?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 No.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 And no children?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 No.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Nothing at all, then.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Not even any sorrow or grief to live upon.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [looking incredulously at her]
\f1\i0 . But, Christine, is that possible?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [smiles sadly and strokes her hair]
\f1\i0 . It sometimes happens, Nora.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 So you are quite alone. How dreadfully sad that must be. I have three lovely children. You can\'92t see them just now, for they are out with their nurse. But now you must tell me all about it.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 No, no; I want to hear about you.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, you must begin. I mustn\'92t be selfish today; today I must only think of your affairs. But there is one thing I must tell you. Do you know we have just had a great piece of good luck?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 No, what is it?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Just fancy, my husband has been made manager of the Bank!\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Your husband? What good luck!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, tremendous! A barrister\'92s profession is such an uncertain thing, especially if he won\'92t undertake unsavoury cases; and naturally Torvald has never been willing to do that, and I quite agree with him. You may imagine how pleased we are! He is to take up his work in the Bank at the New Year, and then he will have a big salary and lots of commissions. For the future we can live quite differently\'97we can do just as we like. I feel so relieved and so happy, Christine! It will be splendid to have heaps of money and not need to have any anxiety, won\'92t it?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Yes, anyhow I think it would be delightful to have what one needs.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, not only what one needs, but heaps and heaps of money.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [smiling]
\f1\i0 . Nora, Nora, haven\'92t you learned sense yet? In our schooldays you were a great spendthrift.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [laughing]
\f1\i0 . Yes, that is what Torvald says now. 
\f0\i [Wags her finger at her.]
\f1\i0  But \'93Nora, Nora\'94 is not so silly as you think. We have not been in a position for me to waste money. We have both had to work.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 You too?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes; odds and ends, needlework, crotchet-work, embroidery, and that kind of thing. 
\f0\i [Dropping her voice.]
\f1\i0  And other things as well. You know Torvald left his office when we were married? There was no prospect of promotion there, and he had to try and earn more than before. But during the first year he over-worked himself dreadfully. You see, he had to make money every way he could, and he worked early and late; but he couldn\'92t stand it, and fell dreadfully ill, and the doctors said it was necessary for him to go south.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 You spent a whole year in Italy, didn\'92t you?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes. It was no easy matter to get away, I can tell you. It was just after Ivar was born; but naturally we had to go. It was a wonderfully beautiful journey, and it saved Torvald\'92s life. But it cost a tremendous lot of money, Christine.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 So I should think.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 It cost about two hundred and fifty pounds. That\'92s a lot, isn\'92t it?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Yes, and in emergencies like that it is lucky to have the money.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I ought to tell you that we had it from papa.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Oh, I see. It was just about that time that he died, wasn\'92t it?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes; and, just think of it, I couldn\'92t go and nurse him. I was expecting little Ivar\'92s birth every day and I had my poor sick Torvald to look after. My dear, kind father\'97I never saw him again, Christine. That was the saddest time I have known since our marriage.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 I know how fond you were of him. And then you went off to Italy?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes; you see we had money then, and the doctors insisted on our going, so we started a month later.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 And your husband came back quite well?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 As sound as a bell!\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 But\'97the doctor?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 What doctor?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 I thought your maid said the gentleman who arrived here just as I did, was the doctor?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, that was Doctor Rank, but he doesn\'92t come here professionally. He is our greatest friend, and comes in at least once every day. No, Torvald has not had an hour\'92s illness since then, and our children are strong and healthy and so am I. 
\f0\i [Jumps up and claps her hands.]
\f1\i0  Christine! Christine! it\'92s good to be alive and happy!\'97But how horrid of me; I am talking of nothing but my own affairs. 
\f0\i [Sits on a stool near her, and rests her arms on her knees.]
\f1\i0  You mustn\'92t be angry with me. Tell me, is it really true that you did not love your husband? Why did you marry him?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 My mother was alive then, and was bedridden and helpless, and I had to provide for my two younger brothers; so I did not think I was justified in refusing his offer.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, perhaps you were quite right. He was rich at that time, then?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 I believe he was quite well off. But his business was a precarious one; and, when he died, it all went to pieces and there was nothing left.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 And then?\'97\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Well, I had to turn my hand to anything I could find\'97first a small shop, then a small school, and so on. The last three years have seemed like one long working-day, with no rest. Now it is at an end, Nora. My poor mother needs me no more, for she is gone; and the boys do not need me either; they have got situations and can shift for themselves.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 What a relief you must feel if\'97\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 No, indeed; I only feel my life unspeakably empty. No one to live for anymore. 
\f0\i [Gets up restlessly.]
\f1\i0  That was why I could not stand the life in my little backwater any longer. I hope it may be easier here to find something which will busy me and occupy my thoughts. If only I could have the good luck to get some regular work\'97office work of some kind\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 But, Christine, that is so frightfully tiring, and you look tired out now. You had far better go away to some watering-place.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [walking to the window]
\f1\i0 . I have no father to give me money for a journey, Nora.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [rising]
\f1\i0 . Oh, don\'92t be angry with me!\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [going up to her]
\f1\i0 . It is you that must not be angry with me, dear. The worst of a position like mine is that it makes one so bitter. No one to work for, and yet obliged to be always on the lookout for chances. One must live, and so one becomes selfish. When you told me of the happy turn your fortunes have taken\'97you will hardly believe it\'97I was delighted not so much on your account as on my own.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 How do you mean?\'97Oh, I understand. You mean that perhaps Torvald could get you something to do.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Yes, that was what I was thinking of.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 He must, Christine. Just leave it to me; I will broach the subject very cleverly\'97I will think of something that will please him very much. It will make me so happy to be of some use to you.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 How kind you are, Nora, to be so anxious to help me! It is doubly kind in you, for you know so little of the burdens and troubles of life.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I\'97? I know so little of them?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [smiling]
\f1\i0 . My dear! Small household cares and that sort of thing!\'97You are a child, Nora.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [tosses her head and crosses the stage]
\f1\i0 . You ought not to be so superior.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 No?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 You are just like the others. They all think that I am incapable of anything really serious\'97\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Come, come\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 \'97that I have gone through nothing in this world of cares.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 But, my dear Nora, you have just told me all your troubles.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Pooh!\'97those were trifles. 
\f0\i [Lowering her voice.]
\f1\i0  I have not told you the important thing.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 The important thing? What do you mean?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 You look down upon me altogether, Christine\'97but you ought not to. You are proud, aren\'92t you, of having worked so hard and so long for your mother?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Indeed, I don\'92t look down on anyone. But it is true that I am both proud and glad to think that I was privileged to make the end of my mother\'92s life almost free from care.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 And you are proud to think of what you have done for your brothers?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 I think I have the right to be.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I think so, too. But now, listen to this; I too have something to be proud and glad of.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 I have no doubt you have. But what do you refer to?\
