KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Oh, there is no necessity to keep up the pretence of ignorance. I can quite understand that your friend is not very anxious to expose herself to the chance of rubbing shoulders with me; and I quite understand, too, whom I have to thank for being turned off.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 But I assure you\'97\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Very likely; but, to come to the point, the time has come when I should advise you to use your influence to prevent that.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 But, Mr. Krogstad, I have no influence.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Haven\'92t you? I thought you said yourself just now\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Naturally I did not mean you to put that construction on it. I! What should make you think I have any influence of that kind with my husband?\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Oh, I have known your husband from our student days. I don\'92t suppose he is any more unassailable than other husbands.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 If you speak slightingly of my husband, I shall turn you out of the house.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 You are bold, Mrs Helmer.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I am not afraid of you any longer. As soon as the New Year comes, I shall in a very short time be free of the whole thing.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [controlling himself]
\f1\i0 . Listen to me, Mrs Helmer. If necessary, I am prepared to fight for my small post in the Bank as if I were fighting for my life.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 So it seems.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 It is not only for the sake of the money; indeed, that weighs least with me in the matter. There is another reason\'97well, I may as well tell you. My position is this. I daresay you know, like everybody else, that once, many years ago, I was guilty of an indiscretion.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I think I have heard something of the kind.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 The matter never came into court; but every way seemed to be closed to me after that. So I took to the business that you know of. I had to do something; and, honestly, I don\'92t think I\'92ve been one of the worst. But now I must cut myself free from all that. My sons are growing up; for their sake I must try and win back as much respect as I can in the town. This post in the Bank was like the first step up for me\'97and now your husband is going to kick me downstairs again into the mud.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 But you must believe me, Mr. Krogstad; it is not in my power to help you at all.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Then it is because you haven\'92t the will; but I have means to compel you.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 You don\'92t mean that you will tell my husband that I owe you money?\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Hm!\'97suppose I were to tell him?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 It would be perfectly infamous of you. 
\f0\i [Sobbing.]
\f1\i0  To think of his learning my secret, which has been my joy and pride, in such an ugly, clumsy way\'97that he should learn it from you! And it would put me in a horribly disagreeable position\'97\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Only disagreeable?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [impetuously]
\f1\i0 . Well, do it, then!\'97and it will be the worse for you. My husband will see for himself what a blackguard you are, and you certainly won\'92t keep your post then.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 I asked you if it was only a disagreeable scene at home that you were afraid of?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 If my husband does get to know of it, of course he will at once pay you what is still owing, and we shall have nothing more to do with you.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [coming a step nearer]
\f1\i0 . Listen to me, Mrs Helmer. Either you have a very bad memory or you know very little of business. I shall be obliged to remind you of a few details.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 What do you mean?\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 When your husband was ill, you came to me to borrow two hundred and fifty pounds.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I didn\'92t know anyone else to go to.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 I promised to get you that amount\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, and you did so.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 I promised to get you that amount, on certain conditions. Your mind was so taken up with your husband\'92s illness, and you were so anxious to get the money for your journey, that you seem to have paid no attention to the conditions of our bargain. Therefore it will not be amiss if I remind you of them. Now, I promised to get the money on the security of a bond which I drew up.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, and which I signed.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Good. But below your signature there were a few lines constituting your father a surety for the money; those lines your father should have signed.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Should? He did sign them.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 I had left the date blank; that is to say, your father should himself have inserted the date on which he signed the paper. Do you remember that?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, I think I remember\'97\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Then I gave you the bond to send by post to your father. Is that not so?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 And you naturally did so at once, because five or six days afterwards you brought me the bond with your father\'92s signature. And then I gave you the money.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Well, haven\'92t I been paying it off regularly?\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Fairly so, yes. But\'97to come back to the matter in hand\'97that must have been a very trying time for you, Mrs Helmer?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 It was, indeed.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Your father was very ill, wasn\'92t he?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 He was very near his end.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 And died soon afterwards?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Tell me, Mrs Helmer, can you by any chance remember what day your father died?\'97on what day of the month, I mean.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Papa died on the 29th of September.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 That is correct; I have ascertained it for myself. And, as that is so, there is a discrepancy 
\f0\i [taking a paper from his pocket]
\f1\i0  which I cannot account for.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 What discrepancy? I don\'92t know\'97\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 The discrepancy consists, Mrs Helmer, in the fact that your father signed this bond three days after his death.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 What do you mean? I don\'92t understand\'97\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Your father died on the 29th of September. But, look here; your father has dated his signature the 2nd of October. It is a discrepancy, isn\'92t it? 
\f0\i [NORA is silent.]
\f1\i0  Can you explain it to me? 
\f0\i [NORA is still silent.]
\f1\i0  It is a remarkable thing, too, that the words \'932nd of October,\'94 as well as the year, are not written in your father\'92s handwriting but in one that I think I know. Well, of course it can be explained; your father may have forgotten to date his signature, and someone else may have dated it haphazard before they knew of his death. There is no harm in that. It all depends on the signature of the name; and that is genuine, I suppose, Mrs Helmer? It was your father himself who signed his name here?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [after a short pause, throws her head up and looks defiantly at him]
\f1\i0 . No, it was not. It was I that wrote papa\'92s name.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Are you aware that is a dangerous confession?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 In what way? You shall have your money soon.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Let me ask you a question; why did you not send the paper to your father?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 It was impossible; papa was so ill. If I had asked him for his signature, I should have had to tell him what the money was to be used for; and when he was so ill himself I couldn\'92t tell him that my husband\'92s life was in danger\'97it was impossible.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 It would have been better for you if you had given up your trip abroad.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, that was impossible. That trip was to save my husband\'92s life; I couldn\'92t give that up.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 But did it never occur to you that you were committing a fraud on me?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I couldn\'92t take that into account; I didn\'92t trouble myself about you at all. I couldn\'92t bear you, because you put so many heartless difficulties in my way, although you knew what a dangerous condition my husband was in.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Mrs Helmer, you evidently do not realise clearly what it is that you have been guilty of. But I can assure you that my one false step, which lost me all my reputation, was nothing more or nothing worse than what you have done.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 You? Do you ask me to believe that you were brave enough to run a risk to save your wife\'92s life?\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 The law cares nothing about motives.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Then it must be a very foolish law.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Foolish or not, it is the law by which you will be judged, if I produce this paper in court.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I don\'92t believe it. Is a daughter not to be allowed to spare her dying father anxiety and care? Is a wife not to be allowed to save her husband\'92s life? I don\'92t know much about law; but I am certain that there must be laws permitting such things as that. Have you no knowledge of such laws\'97you who are a lawyer? You must be a very poor lawyer, Mr. Krogstad.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Maybe. But matters of business\'97such business as you and I have had together\'97do you think I don\'92t understand that? Very well. Do as you please. But let me tell you this\'97if I lose my position a second time, you shall lose yours with me. 
\f0\i [He bows, and goes out through the hall.]
\f1\i0 \
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [appears buried in thought for a short time, then tosses her head]
\f1\i0 . Nonsense! Trying to frighten me like that!\'97I am not so silly as he thinks. 
\f0\i [Begins to busy herself putting the children\'92s things in order.]
\f1\i0  And yet\'97? No, it\'92s impossible! I did it for love\'92s sake.\
THE CHILDREN.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [in the doorway on the left]
\f1\i0 . Mother, the stranger man has gone out through the gate.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, dears, I know. But, don\'92t tell anyone about the stranger man. Do you hear? Not even papa.\
CHILDREN.\uc0\u8232 No, mother; but will you come and play again?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, no,\'97not now.\
CHILDREN.\uc0\u8232 But, mother, you promised us.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, but I can\'92t now. Run away in; I have such a lot to do. Run away in, my sweet little darlings. 
\f0\i [She gets them into the room by degrees and shuts the door on them; then sits down on the sofa, takes up a piece of needlework and sews a few stitches, but soon stops.]
\f1\i0  No! 
\f0\i [Throws down the work, gets up, goes to the hall door and calls out.]
\f1\i0  Helen! bring the Tree in. 
\f0\i [Goes to the table on the left, opens a drawer, and stops again.]
\f1\i0  No, no! it is quite impossible!\
MAID.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [coming in with the Tree]
\f1\i0 . Where shall I put it, ma\'92am?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Here, in the middle of the floor.\
MAID.\uc0\u8232 Shall I get you anything else?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, thank you. I have all I want. [Exit MAID.]\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [begins dressing the tree]
\f1\i0 . A candle here-and flowers here\'97The horrible man! It\'92s all nonsense\'97there\'92s nothing wrong. The tree shall be splendid! I will do everything I can think of to please you, Torvald!\'97I will sing for you, dance for you\'97
\f0\i [HELMER comes in with some papers under his arm.]
\f1\i0  Oh! are you back already?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Yes. Has anyone been here?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Here? No.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 That is strange. I saw Krogstad going out of the gate.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Did you? Oh yes, I forgot, Krogstad was here for a moment.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Nora, I can see from your manner that he has been here begging you to say a good word for him.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 And you were to appear to do it of your own accord; you were to conceal from me the fact of his having been here; didn\'92t he beg that of you too?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, Torvald, but\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Nora, Nora, and you would be a party to that sort of thing? To have any talk with a man like that, and give him any sort of promise? And to tell me a lie into the bargain?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 A lie\'97?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Didn\'92t you tell me no one had been here? 
\f0\i [Shakes his finger at her.]
\f1\i0  My little songbird must never do that again. A songbird must have a clean beak to chirp with\'97no false notes! 
\f0\i [Puts his arm round her waist.]
\f1\i0  That is so, isn\'92t it? Yes, I am sure it is. 
\f0\i [Lets her go.]
\f1\i0  We will say no more about it. 
\f0\i [Sits down by the stove.]
\f1\i0  How warm and snug it is here! 
\f0\i [Turns over his papers.]
\f1\i0 \
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [after a short pause, during which she busies herself with the Christmas Tree.]
\f1\i0  Torvald!\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Yes.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I am looking forward tremendously to the fancy-dress ball at the Stenborgs\'92 the day after tomorrow.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 And I am tremendously curious to see what you are going to surprise me with.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 It was very silly of me to want to do that.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 What do you mean?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I can\'92t hit upon anything that will do; everything I think of seems so silly and insignificant.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Does my little Nora acknowledge that at last?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [standing behind his chair with her arms on the back of it]
\f1\i0 . Are you very busy, Torvald?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Well\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 What are all those papers?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Bank business.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Already?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 I have got authority from the retiring manager to undertake the necessary changes in the staff and in the rearrangement of the work; and I must make use of the Christmas week for that, so as to have everything in order for the new year.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Then that was why this poor Krogstad\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Hm!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [leans against the back of his chair and strokes his hair]
\f1\i0 . If you hadn\'92t been so busy I should have asked you a tremendously big favour, Torvald.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 What is that? Tell me.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 There is no one has such good taste as you. And I do so want to look nice at the fancy-dress ball. Torvald, couldn\'92t you take me in hand and decide what I shall go as, and what sort of a dress I shall wear?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Aha! so my obstinate little woman is obliged to get someone to come to her rescue?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, Torvald, I can\'92t get along a bit without your help.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Very well, I will think it over, we shall manage to hit upon something.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 That is nice of you. 
\f0\i [Goes to the Christmas Tree. A short pause.]
\f1\i0  How pretty the red flowers look\'97. But, tell me, was it really something very bad that this Krogstad was guilty of?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 He forged someone\'92s name. Have you any idea what that means?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Isn\'92t it possible that he was driven to do it by necessity?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Yes; or, as in so many cases, by imprudence. I am not so heartless as to condemn a man altogether because of a single false step of that kind.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, you wouldn\'92t, would you, Torvald?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Many a man has been able to retrieve his character, if he has openly confessed his fault and taken his punishment.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Punishment\'97?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 But Krogstad did nothing of that sort; he got himself out of it by a cunning trick, and that is why he has gone under altogether.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 But do you think it would\'97?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Just think how a guilty man like that has to lie and play the hypocrite with every one, how he has to wear a mask in the presence of those near and dear to him, even before his own wife and children. And about the children\'97that is the most terrible part of it all, Nora.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 How?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Because such an atmosphere of lies infects and poisons the whole life of a home. Each breath the children take in such a house is full of the germs of evil.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [coming nearer him]
\f1\i0 . Are you sure of that?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 My dear, I have often seen it in the course of my life as a lawyer. Almost everyone who has gone to the bad early in life has had a deceitful mother.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Why do you only say\'97mother?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 It seems most commonly to be the mother\'92s influence, though naturally a bad father\'92s would have the same result. Every lawyer is familiar with the fact. This Krogstad, now, has been persistently poisoning his own children with lies and dissimulation; that is why I say he has lost all moral character. 
\f0\i [Holds out his hands to her.]
\f1\i0  That is why my sweet little Nora must promise me not to plead his cause. Give me your hand on it. Come, come, what is this? Give me your hand. There now, that\'92s settled. I assure you it would be quite impossible for me to work with him; I literally feel physically ill when I am in the company of such people.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [takes her hand out of his and goes to the opposite side of the Christmas Tree]
\f1\i0 . How hot it is in here; and I have such a lot to do.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [getting up and putting his papers in order]
\f1\i0 . Yes, and I must try and read through some of these before dinner; and I must think about your costume, too. And it is just possible I may have something ready in gold paper to hang up on the Tree. 
\f0\i [Puts his hand on her head.]
\f1\i0  My precious little singing-bird! 
\f0\i [He goes into his room and shuts the door after him.]
\f1\i0 \
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [after a pause, whispers]
\f1\i0 . No, no\'97it isn\'92t true. It\'92s impossible; it must be impossible.\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi320\sa80\qj\partightenfactor0

\f0\i \cf0 [The NURSE opens the door on the left.]
\f1\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 NURSE.\uc0\u8232 The little ones are begging so hard to be allowed to come in to mamma.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, no, no! Don\'92t let them come in to me! You stay with them, Anne.\
NURSE.\uc0\u8232 Very well, ma\'92am. 
\f0\i [Shuts the door.]
\f1\i0 \
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [pale with terror]
\f1\i0 . Deprave my little children? Poison my home? 
\f0\i [A short pause. Then she tosses her head.]
\f1\i0  It\'92s not true. It can\'92t possibly be true. \uc0\u8232 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa480\qc\partightenfactor0

\fs48 \cf0 ACT II\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi320\sa80\qj\partightenfactor0

\f0\i\fs32 \cf0 [THE SAME SCENE.\'97THE Christmas Tree is in the corner by the piano, stripped of its ornaments and with burnt-down candle-ends on its dishevelled branches. NORA\'92S cloak and hat are lying on the sofa. She is alone in the room, walking about uneasily. She stops by the sofa and takes up her cloak.]
\f1\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [drops her cloak]
\f1\i0 . Someone is coming now! 
\f0\i [Goes to the door and listens.]
\f1\i0  No\'97it is no one. Of course, no one will come today, Christmas Day\'97nor tomorrow either. But, perhaps\'97
\f0\i [opens the door and looks out]
\f1\i0 . No, nothing in the letterbox; it is quite empty. 
\f0\i [Comes forward.]
\f1\i0  What rubbish! of course he can\'92t be in earnest about it. Such a thing couldn\'92t happen; it is impossible\'97I have three little children.\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi320\sa80\qj\partightenfactor0

\f0\i \cf0 [Enter the NURSE from the room on the left, carrying a big cardboard box.]
\f1\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 NURSE.\uc0\u8232 At last I have found the box with the fancy dress.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Thanks; put it on the table.\
NURSE.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [doing so]
\f1\i0 . But it is very much in want of mending.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I should like to tear it into a hundred thousand pieces.\
NURSE.\uc0\u8232 What an idea! It can easily be put in order\'97just a little patience.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, I will go and get Mrs Linde to come and help me with it.\
NURSE.\uc0\u8232 What, out again? In this horrible weather? You will catch cold, ma\'92am, and make yourself ill.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Well, worse than that might happen. How are the children?\
NURSE.\uc0\u8232 The poor little souls are playing with their Christmas presents, but\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Do they ask much for me?\
NURSE.\uc0\u8232 You see, they are so accustomed to have their mamma with them.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, but, nurse, I shall not be able to be so much with them now as I was before.\
NURSE.\uc0\u8232 Oh well, young children easily get accustomed to anything.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Do you think so? Do you think they would forget their mother if she went away altogether?\
NURSE.\uc0\u8232 Good heavens!\'97went away altogether?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Nurse, I want you to tell me something I have often wondered about\'97how could you have the heart to put your own child out among strangers?\
NURSE.\uc0\u8232 I was obliged to, if I wanted to be little Nora\'92s nurse.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, but how could you be willing to do it?\
NURSE.\uc0\u8232 What, when I was going to get such a good place by it? A poor girl who has got into trouble should be glad to. Besides, that wicked man didn\'92t do a single thing for me.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 But I suppose your daughter has quite forgotten you.\
NURSE.\uc0\u8232 No, indeed she hasn\'92t. She wrote to me when she was confirmed, and when she was married.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [putting her arms round her neck]
\f1\i0 . Dear old Anne, you were a good mother to me when I was little.\
NURSE.\uc0\u8232 Little Nora, poor dear, had no other mother but me.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 And if my little ones had no other mother, I am sure you would\'97What nonsense I am talking! 
\f0\i [Opens the box.]
\f1\i0  Go in to them. Now I must\'97. You will see tomorrow how charming I shall look.\
NURSE.\uc0\u8232 I am sure there will be no one at the ball so charming as you, ma\'92am. 
\f0\i [Goes into the room on the left.]
\f1\i0 \
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [begins to unpack the box, but soon pushes it away from her]
\f1\i0 . If only I dared go out. If only no one would come. If only I could be sure nothing would happen here in the meantime. Stuff and nonsense! No one will come. Only I mustn\'92t think about it. I will brush my muff. What lovely, lovely gloves! Out of my thoughts, out of my thoughts! One, two, three, four, five, six\'97 
\f0\i [Screams.]
\f1\i0  Ah! there is someone coming\'97. 
\f0\i [Makes a movement towards the door, but stands irresolute.]
\f1\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi320\sa80\qj\partightenfactor0

\f0\i \cf0 [Enter Mrs Linde from the hall, where she has taken off her cloak and hat.]
\f1\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 NORA.\uc0\u8232 Oh, it\'92s you, Christine. There is no one else out there, is there? How good of you to come!\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 I heard you were up asking for me.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, I was passing by. As a matter of fact, it is something you could help me with. Let us sit down here on the sofa. Look here. Tomorrow evening there is to be a fancy-dress ball at the Stenborgs\'92, who live above us; and Torvald wants me to go as a Neapolitan fisher-girl, and dance the Tarantella that I learned at Capri.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 I see; you are going to keep up the character.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, Torvald wants me to. Look, here is the dress; Torvald had it made for me there, but now it is all so torn, and I haven\'92t any idea\'97\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 We will easily put that right. It is only some of the trimming come unsewn here and there. Needle and thread? Now then, that\'92s all we want.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 It is nice of you.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [sewing]
\f1\i0 . So you are going to be dressed up tomorrow Nora. I will tell you what\'97I shall come in for a moment and see you in your fine feathers. But I have completely forgotten to thank you for a delightful evening yesterday.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [gets up, and crosses the stage]
\f1\i0 . Well, I don\'92t think yesterday was as pleasant as usual. You ought to have come to town a little earlier, Christine. Certainly Torvald does understand how to make a house dainty and attractive.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 And so do you, it seems to me; you are not your father\'92s daughter for nothing. But tell me, is Doctor Rank always as depressed as he was yesterday?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No; yesterday it was very noticeable. I must tell you that he suffers from a very dangerous disease. He has consumption of the spine, poor creature. His father was a horrible man who committed all sorts of excesses; and that is why his son was sickly from childhood, do you understand?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [dropping her sewing]
\f1\i0 . But, my dearest Nora, how do you know anything about such things?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [walking about]
\f1\i0 . Pooh! When you have three children, you get visits now and then from\'97from married women, who know something of medical matters, and they talk about one thing and another.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [goes on sewing. A short silence]
\f1\i0 . Does Doctor Rank come here everyday?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Everyday regularly. He is Torvald\'92s most intimate friend, and a great friend of mine too. He is just like one of the family.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 But tell me this\'97is he perfectly sincere? I mean, isn\'92t he the kind of man that is very anxious to make himself agreeable?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Not in the least. What makes you think that?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 When you introduced him to me yesterday, he declared he had often heard my name mentioned in this house; but afterwards I noticed that your husband hadn\'92t the slightest idea who I was. So how could Doctor Rank\'97?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 That is quite right, Christine. Torvald is so absurdly fond of me that he wants me absolutely to himself, as he says. At first he used to seem almost jealous if I mentioned any of the dear folk at home, so naturally I gave up doing so. But I often talk about such things with Doctor Rank, because he likes hearing about them.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Listen to me, Nora. You are still very like a child in many things, and I am older than you in many ways and have a little more experience. Let me tell you this\'97you ought to make an end of it with Doctor Rank.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 What ought I to make an end of?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Of two things, I think. Yesterday you talked some nonsense about a rich admirer who was to leave you money\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 An admirer who doesn\'92t exist, unfortunately! But what then?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Is Doctor Rank a man of means?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, he is.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 And has no one to provide for?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, no one; but\'97\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 And comes here everyday?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, I told you so.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 But how can this well-bred man be so tactless?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I don\'92t understand you at all.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Don\'92t prevaricate, Nora. Do you suppose I don\'92t guess who lent you the two hundred and fifty pounds?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Are you out of your senses? How can you think of such a thing! A friend of ours, who comes here everyday! Do you realise what a horribly painful position that would be?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Then it really isn\'92t he?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, certainly not. It would never have entered into my head for a moment. Besides, he had no money to lend then; he came into his money afterwards.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Well, I think that was lucky for you, my dear Nora.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, it would never have come into my head to ask Doctor Rank. Although I am quite sure that if I had asked him\'97\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 But of course you won\'92t.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Of course not. I have no reason to think it could possibly be necessary. But I am quite sure that if I told Doctor Rank\'97\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Behind your husband\'92s back?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I must make an end of it with the other one, and that will be behind his back too. I must make an end of it with him.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Yes, that is what I told you yesterday, but\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [walking up and down]
\f1\i0 . A man can put a thing like that straight much easier than a woman\'97\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 One\'92s husband, yes.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Nonsense! 
\f0\i [Standing still.]
\f1\i0  When you pay off a debt you get your bond back, don\'92t you?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Yes, as a matter of course.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 And can tear it into a hundred thousand pieces, and burn it up\'97the nasty dirty paper!\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [looks hard at her, lays down her sewing and gets up slowly]
\f1\i0 . Nora, you are concealing something from me.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Do I look as if I were?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Something has happened to you since yesterday morning. Nora, what is it?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [going nearer to her]
\f1\i0 . Christine! 
\f0\i [Listens.]
\f1\i0  Hush! there\'92s Torvald come home. Do you mind going in to the children for the present? Torvald can\'92t bear to see dressmaking going on. Let Anne help you.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [gathering some of the things together]
\f1\i0 . Certainly\'97but I am not going away from here until we have had it out with one another. 
\f0\i [She goes into the room on the left, as HELMER comes in from the hall.]
\f1\i0 \
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [going up to HELMER]
\f1\i0 . I have wanted you so much, Torvald dear.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Was that the dressmaker?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, it was Christine; she is helping me to put my dress in order. You will see I shall look quite smart.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Wasn\'92t that a happy thought of mine, now?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Splendid! But don\'92t you think it is nice of me, too, to do as you wish?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Nice?\'97because you do as your husband wishes? Well, well, you little rogue, I am sure you did not mean it in that way. But I am not going to disturb you; you will want to be trying on your dress, I expect.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I suppose you are going to work.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Yes. 
\f0\i [Shows her a bundle of papers.]
\f1\i0  Look at that. I have just been into the bank. 
\f0\i [Turns to go into his room.]
\f1\i0 \
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Torvald.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Yes.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 If your little squirrel were to ask you for something very, very prettily\'97?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 What then?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Would you do it?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 I should like to hear what it is, first.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Your squirrel would run about and do all her tricks if you would be nice, and do what she wants.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Speak plainly.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Your skylark would chirp about in every room, with her song rising and falling\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Well, my skylark does that anyhow.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I would play the fairy and dance for you in the moonlight, Torvald.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Nora\'97you surely don\'92t mean that request you made to me this morning?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [going near him]
\f1\i0 . Yes, Torvald, I beg you so earnestly\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Have you really the courage to open up that question again?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, dear, you must do as I ask; you must let Krogstad keep his post in the bank.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 My dear Nora, it is his post that I have arranged Mrs Linde shall have.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, you have been awfully kind about that; but you could just as well dismiss some other clerk instead of Krogstad.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 This is simply incredible obstinacy! Because you chose to give him a thoughtless promise that you would speak for him, I am expected to\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 That isn\'92t the reason, Torvald. It is for your own sake. This fellow writes in the most scurrilous newspapers; you have told me so yourself. He can do you an unspeakable amount of harm. I am frightened to death of him\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Ah, I understand; it is recollections of the past that scare you.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 What do you mean?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Naturally you are thinking of your father.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes\'97yes, of course. Just recall to your mind what these malicious creatures wrote in the papers about papa, and how horribly they slandered him. I believe they would have procured his dismissal if the Department had not sent you over to inquire into it, and if you had not been so kindly disposed and helpful to him.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 My little Nora, there is an important difference between your father and me. Your father\'92s reputation as a public official was not above suspicion. Mine is, and I hope it will continue to be so, as long as I hold my office.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 You never can tell what mischief these men may contrive. We ought to be so well off, so snug and happy here in our peaceful home, and have no cares\'97you and I and the children, Torvald! That is why I beg you so earnestly\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 And it is just by interceding for him that you make it impossible for me to keep him. It is already known at the Bank that I mean to dismiss Krogstad. Is it to get about now that the new manager has changed his mind at his wife\'92s bidding\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 And what if it did?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Of course!\'97if only this obstinate little person can get her way! Do you suppose I am going to make myself ridiculous before my whole staff, to let people think that I am a man to be swayed by all sorts of outside influence? I should very soon feel the consequences of it, I can tell you! And besides, there is one thing that makes it quite impossible for me to have Krogstad in the Bank as long as I am manager.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Whatever is that?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 His moral failings I might perhaps have overlooked, if necessary\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, you could\'97couldn\'92t you?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 And I hear he is a good worker, too. But I knew him when we were boys. It was one of those rash friendships that so often prove an incubus in afterlife. I may as well tell you plainly, we were once on very intimate terms with one another. But this tactless fellow lays no restraint on himself when other people are present. On the contrary, he thinks it gives him the right to adopt a familiar tone with me, and every minute it is \'93I say, Helmer, old fellow!\'94 and that sort of thing. I assure you it is extremely painful for me. He would make my position in the Bank intolerable.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Torvald, I don\'92t believe you mean that.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Don\'92t you? Why not?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Because it is such a narrow-minded way of looking at things.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 What are you saying? Narrow-minded? Do you think I am narrow-minded?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, just the opposite, dear\'97and it is exactly for that reason.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 It\'92s the same thing. You say my point of view is narrow-minded, so I must be so too. Narrow-minded! Very well\'97I must put an end to this. 
\f0\i [Goes to the hall door and calls.]
\f1\i0  Helen!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 What are you going to do?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [looking among his papers]
\f1\i0 . Settle it. 
\f0\i [Enter MAID.]
\f1\i0  Look here; take this letter and go downstairs with it at once. Find a messenger and tell him to deliver it, and be quick. The address is on it, and here is the money.\
MAID.\uc0\u8232 Very well, sir. 
\f0\i [Exit with the letter.]
\f1\i0 \
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [putting his papers together]
\f1\i0 . Now then, little Miss Obstinate.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [breathlessly]
\f1\i0 . Torvald\'97what was that letter?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Krogstad\'92s dismissal.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Call her back, Torvald! There is still time. Oh Torvald, call her back! Do it for my sake\'97for your own sake\'97for the children\'92s sake! Do you hear me, Torvald? Call her back! You don\'92t know what that letter can bring upon us.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 It\'92s too late.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, it\'92s too late.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 My dear Nora, I can forgive the anxiety you are in, although really it is an insult to me. It is, indeed. Isn\'92t it an insult to think that I should be afraid of a starving quill-driver\'92s vengeance? But I forgive you nevertheless, because it is such eloquent witness to your great love for me. 
\f0\i [Takes her in his arms.]
\f1\i0  And that is as it should be, my own darling Nora. Come what will, you may be sure I shall have both courage and strength if they be needed. You will see I am man enough to take everything upon myself.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [in a horror-stricken voice]
\f1\i0 . What do you mean by that?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Everything, I say\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [recovering herself]
\f1\i0 . You will never have to do that.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 That\'92s right. Well, we will share it, Nora, as man and wife should. That is how it shall be. 
\f0\i [Caressing her.]
\f1\i0  Are you content now? There! There!\'97not these frightened dove\'92s eyes! The whole thing is only the wildest fancy!\'97Now, you must go and play through the Tarantella and practise with your tambourine. I shall go into the inner office and shut the door, and I shall hear nothing; you can make as much noise as you please. 
\f0\i [Turns back at the door.]
\f1\i0  And when Rank comes, tell him where he will find me. 
\f0\i [Nods to her, takes his papers and goes into his room, and shuts the door after him.]
\f1\i0 \
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [bewildered with anxiety, stands as if rooted to the spot, and whispers]
\f1\i0 . He was capable of doing it. He will do it. He will do it in spite of everything.\'97No, not that! Never, never! Anything rather than that! Oh, for some help, some way out of it! 
\f0\i [The door-bell rings.]
\f1\i0  Doctor Rank! Anything rather than that\'97anything, whatever it is! 
\f0\i [She puts her hands over her face, pulls herself together, goes to the door and opens it. RANK is standing without, hanging up his coat. During the following dialogue it begins to grow dark.]
\f1\i0 \
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Good day, Doctor Rank. I knew your ring. But you mustn\'92t go in to Torvald now; I think he is busy with something.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 And you?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [brings him in and shuts the door after him]
\f1\i0 . Oh, you know very well I always have time for you.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Thank you. I shall make use of as much of it as I can.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 What do you mean by that? As much of it as you can?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Well, does that alarm you?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 It was such a strange way of putting it. Is anything likely to happen?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Nothing but what I have long been prepared for. But I certainly didn\'92t expect it to happen so soon.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [gripping him by the arm]
\f1\i0 . What have you found out? Doctor Rank, you must tell me.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [sitting down by the stove]
\f1\i0 . It is all up with me. And it can\'92t be helped.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [with a sigh of relief]
\f1\i0 . Is it about yourself?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Who else? It is no use lying to one\'92s self. I am the most wretched of all my patients, Mrs Helmer. Lately I have been taking stock of my internal economy. Bankrupt! Probably within a month I shall lie rotting in the churchyard.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 What an ugly thing to say!\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 The thing itself is cursedly ugly, and the worst of it is that I shall have to face so much more that is ugly before that. I shall only make one more examination of myself; when I have done that, I shall know pretty certainly when it will be that the horrors of dissolution will begin. There is something I want to tell you. Helmer\'92s refined nature gives him an unconquerable disgust at everything that is ugly; I won\'92t have him in my sick-room.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Oh, but, Doctor Rank\'97\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 I won\'92t have him there. Not on any account. I bar my door to him. As soon as I am quite certain that the worst has come, I shall send you my card with a black cross on it, and then you will know that the loathsome end has begun.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 You are quite absurd today. And I wanted you so much to be in a really good humour.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 With death stalking beside me?\'97To have to pay this penalty for another man\'92s sin? Is there any justice in that? And in every single family, in one way or another, some such inexorable retribution is being exacted\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [putting her hands over her ears]
\f1\i0 . Rubbish! Do talk of something cheerful.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Oh, it\'92s a mere laughing matter, the whole thing. My poor innocent spine has to suffer for my father\'92s youthful amusements.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [sitting at the table on the left]
\f1\i0 . I suppose you mean that he was too partial to asparagus and pate de foie gras, don\'92t you?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Yes, and to truffles.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Truffles, yes. And oysters too, I suppose?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Oysters, of course, that goes without saying.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 And heaps of port and champagne. It is sad that all these nice things should take their revenge on our bones.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Especially that they should revenge themselves on the unlucky bones of those who have not had the satisfaction of enjoying them.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, that\'92s the saddest part of it all.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [with a searching look at her]
\f1\i0 . Hm!\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [after a short pause]
\f1\i0 . Why did you smile?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 No, it was you that laughed.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, it was you that smiled, Doctor Rank!\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [rising]
\f1\i0 . You are a greater rascal than I thought.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I am in a silly mood today.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 So it seems.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [putting her hands on his shoulders]
\f1\i0 . Dear, dear Doctor Rank, death mustn\'92t take you away from Torvald and me.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 It is a loss you would easily recover from. Those who are gone are soon forgotten.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [looking at him anxiously]
\f1\i0 . Do you believe that?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 People form new ties, and then\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Who will form new ties?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Both you and Helmer, when I am gone. You yourself are already on the high road to it, I think. What did that Mrs Linde want here last night?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Oho!\'97you don\'92t mean to say you are jealous of poor Christine?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Yes, I am. She will be my successor in this house. When I am done for, this woman will\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Hush! don\'92t speak so loud. She is in that room.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Today again. There, you see.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 She has only come to sew my dress for me. Bless my soul, how unreasonable you are! 
\f0\i [Sits down on the sofa.]
\f1\i0  Be nice now, Doctor Rank, and tomorrow you will see how beautifully I shall dance, and you can imagine I am doing it all for you\'97and for Torvald too, of course. 
\f0\i [Takes various things out of the box.]
\f1\i0  Doctor Rank, come and sit down here, and I will show you something.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [sitting down]
\f1\i0 . What is it?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Just look at those!\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Silk stockings.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Flesh-coloured. Aren\'92t they lovely? It is so dark here now, but tomorrow\'97. No, no, no! you must only look at the feet. Oh well, you may have leave to look at the legs too.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Hm!\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Why are you looking so critical? Don\'92t you think they will fit me?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 I have no means of forming an opinion about that.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [looks at him for a moment]
\f1\i0 . For shame! 
\f0\i [Hits him lightly on the ear with the stockings.]
\f1\i0  That\'92s to punish you. 
\f0\i [Folds them up again.]
\f1\i0 \
RANK.\uc0\u8232 And what other nice things am I to be allowed to see?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Not a single thing more, for being so naughty. 
\f0\i [She looks among the things, humming to herself.]
\f1\i0 \
RANK.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [after a short silence]
\f1\i0 . When I am sitting here, talking to you as intimately as this, I cannot imagine for a moment what would have become of me if I had never come into this house.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [smiling]
\f1\i0 . I believe you do feel thoroughly at home with us.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [in a lower voice, looking straight in front of him]
\f1\i0 . And to be obliged to leave it all\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Nonsense, you are not going to leave it.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [as before]
\f1\i0 . And not be able to leave behind one the slightest token of one\'92s gratitude, scarcely even a fleeting regret\'97nothing but an empty place which the first comer can fill as well as any other.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 And if I asked you now for a\'97? No!\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 For what?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 For a big proof of your friendship\'97\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Yes, yes!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I mean a tremendously big favour\'97\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Would you really make me so happy for once?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Ah, but you don\'92t know what it is yet.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 No\'97but tell me.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I really can\'92t, Doctor Rank. It is something out of all reason; it means advice, and help, and a favour\'97\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 The bigger a thing it is the better. I can\'92t conceive what it is you mean. Do tell me. Haven\'92t I your confidence?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 More than anyone else. I know you are my truest and best friend, and so I will tell you what it is. Well, Doctor Rank, it is something you must help me to prevent. You know how devotedly, how inexpressibly deeply Torvald loves me; he would never for a moment hesitate to give his life for me.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [leaning towards her]
\f1\i0 . Nora\'97do you think he is the only one\'97?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [with a slight start]
\f1\i0 . The only one\'97?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 The only one who would gladly give his life for your sake.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [sadly]
\f1\i0 . Is that it?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 I was determined you should know it before I went away, and there will never be a better opportunity than this. Now you know it, Nora. And now you know, too, that you can trust me as you would trust no one else.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [rises, deliberately and quietly]
\f1\i0 . Let me pass.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [makes room for her to pass him, but sits still]
\f1\i0 . Nora!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [at the hall door]
\f1\i0 . Helen, bring in the lamp. 
\f0\i [Goes over to the stove.]
\f1\i0  Dear Doctor Rank, that was really horrid of you.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 To have loved you as much as anyone else does? Was that horrid?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, but to go and tell me so. There was really no need\'97\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 What do you mean? Did you know\'97? 
\f0\i [MAID enters with lamp, puts it down on the table, and goes out.]
\f1\i0  Nora\'97Mrs Helmer\'97tell me, had you any idea of this?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Oh, how do I know whether I had or whether I hadn\'92t? I really can\'92t tell you\'97To think you could be so clumsy, Doctor Rank! We were getting on so nicely.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Well, at all events you know now that you can command me, body and soul. So won\'92t you speak out?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [looking at him]
\f1\i0 . After what happened?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 I beg you to let me know what it is.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I can\'92t tell you anything now.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Yes, yes. You mustn\'92t punish me in that way. Let me have permission to do for you whatever a man may do.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 You can do nothing for me now. Besides, I really don\'92t need any help at all. You will find that the whole thing is merely fancy on my part. It really is so\'97of course it is! 
