\f0\i [Listens again.]
\f1\i0  Ah, there he is. 
\f0\i [Goes into the hall and opens the outer door carefully. Light footsteps are heard on the stairs. She whispers.]
\f1\i0  Come in. There is no one here.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [in the doorway]
\f1\i0 . I found a note from you at home. What does this mean?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 It is absolutely necessary that I should have a talk with you.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Really? And is it absolutely necessary that it should be here?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 It is impossible where I live; there is no private entrance to my rooms. Come in; we are quite alone. The maid is asleep, and the Helmers are at the dance upstairs.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [coming into the room]
\f1\i0 . Are the Helmers really at a dance tonight?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Yes, why not?\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Certainly\'97why not?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Now, Nils, let us have a talk.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Can we two have anything to talk about?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 We have a great deal to talk about.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 I shouldn\'92t have thought so.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 No, you have never properly understood me.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Was there anything else to understand except what was obvious to all the world\'97a heartless woman jilts a man when a more lucrative chance turns up?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Do you believe I am as absolutely heartless as all that? And do you believe that I did it with a light heart?\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Didn\'92t you?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Nils, did you really think that?\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 If it were as you say, why did you write to me as you did at the time?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 I could do nothing else. As I had to break with you, it was my duty also to put an end to all that you felt for me.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [wringing his hands]
\f1\i0 . So that was it. And all this\'97only for the sake of money!\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 You must not forget that I had a helpless mother and two little brothers. We couldn\'92t wait for you, Nils; your prospects seemed hopeless then.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 That may be so, but you had no right to throw me over for anyone else\'92s sake.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Indeed I don\'92t know. Many a time did I ask myself if I had the right to do it.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [more gently]
\f1\i0 . When I lost you, it was as if all the solid ground went from under my feet. Look at me now\'97I am a shipwrecked man clinging to a bit of wreckage.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 But help may be near.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 It was near; but then you came and stood in my way.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Unintentionally, Nils. It was only today that I learned it was your place I was going to take in the Bank.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 I believe you, if you say so. But now that you know it, are you not going to give it up to me?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 No, because that would not benefit you in the least.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Oh, benefit, benefit\'97I would have done it whether or no.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 I have learned to act prudently. Life, and hard, bitter necessity have taught me that.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 And life has taught me not to believe in fine speeches.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Then life has taught you something very reasonable. But deeds you must believe in?\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 What do you mean by that?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 You said you were like a shipwrecked man clinging to some wreckage.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 I had good reason to say so.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Well, I am like a shipwrecked woman clinging to some wreckage\'97no one to mourn for, no one to care for.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 It was your own choice.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 There was no other choice\'97then.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Well, what now?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Nils, how would it be if we two shipwrecked people could join forces?\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 What are you saying?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Two on the same piece of wreckage would stand a better chance than each on their own.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Christine I...\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 What do you suppose brought me to town?\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Do you mean that you gave me a thought?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 I could not endure life without work. All my life, as long as I can remember, I have worked, and it has been my greatest and only pleasure. But now I am quite alone in the world\'97my life is so dreadfully empty and I feel so forsaken. There is not the least pleasure in working for one\'92s self. Nils, give me someone and something to work for.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 I don\'92t trust that. It is nothing but a woman\'92s overstrained sense of generosity that prompts you to make such an offer of yourself.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Have you ever noticed anything of the sort in me?\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Could you really do it? Tell me\'97do you know all about my past life?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Yes.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 And do you know what they think of me here?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 You seemed to me to imply that with me you might have been quite another man.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 I am certain of it.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Is it too late now?\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Christine, are you saying this deliberately? Yes, I am sure you are. I see it in your face. Have you really the courage, then\'97?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 I want to be a mother to someone, and your children need a mother. We two need each other. Nils, I have faith in your real character\'97I can dare anything together with you.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [grasps her hands]
\f1\i0 . Thanks, thanks, Christine! Now I shall find a way to clear myself in the eyes of the world. Ah, but I forgot\'97\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [listening]
\f1\i0 . Hush! The Tarantella! Go, go!\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Why? What is it?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Do you hear them up there? When that is over, we may expect them back.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Yes, yes\'97I will go. But it is all no use. Of course you are not aware what steps I have taken in the matter of the Helmers.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Yes, I know all about that.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 And in spite of that have you the courage to\'97?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 I understand very well to what lengths a man like you might be driven by despair.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 If I could only undo what I have done!\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 You cannot. Your letter is lying in the letter-box now.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Are you sure of that?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Quite sure, but\'97\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [with a searching look at her]
\f1\i0 . Is that what it all means?\'97that you want to save your friend at any cost? Tell me frankly. Is that it?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Nils, a woman who has once sold herself for another\'92s sake, doesn\'92t do it a second time.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 I will ask for my letter back.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 No, no.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Yes, of course I will. I will wait here until Helmer comes; I will tell him he must give me my letter back\'97that it only concerns my dismissal\'97that he is not to read it\'97\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 No, Nils, you must not recall your letter.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 But, tell me, wasn\'92t it for that very purpose that you asked me to meet you here?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 In my first moment of fright, it was. But twenty-four hours have elapsed since then, and in that time I have witnessed incredible things in this house. Helmer must know all about it. This unhappy secret must be disclosed; they must have a complete understanding between them, which is impossible with all this concealment and falsehood going on.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 Very well, if you will take the responsibility. But there is one thing I can do in any case, and I shall do it at once.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [listening]
\f1\i0 . You must be quick and go! The dance is over; we are not safe a moment longer.\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 I will wait for you below.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Yes, do. You must see me back to my door...\
KROGSTAD.\uc0\u8232 I have never had such an amazing piece of good fortune in my life! 
\f0\i [Goes out through the outer door. The door between the room and the hall remains open.]
\f1\i0 \
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [tidying up the room and laying her hat and cloak ready]
\f1\i0 . What a difference! what a difference! Someone to work for and live for\'97a home to bring comfort into. That I will do, indeed. I wish they would be quick and come\'97
\f0\i [Listens.]
\f1\i0  Ah, there they are now. I must put on my things. 
\f0\i [Takes up her hat and cloak. HELMER\'92S and NORA\'92S voices are heard outside; a key is turned, and HELMER brings NORA almost by force into the hall. She is in an Italian costume with a large black shawl around her; he is in evening dress, and a black domino which is flying open.]
\f1\i0 \
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [hanging back in the doorway, and struggling with him]
\f1\i0 . No, no, no!\'97don\'92t take me in. I want to go upstairs again; I don\'92t want to leave so early.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 But, my dearest Nora\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Please, Torvald dear\'97please, please\'97only an hour more.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Not a single minute, my sweet Nora. You know that was our agreement. Come along into the room; you are catching cold standing there. 
\f0\i [He brings her gently into the room, in spite of her resistance.]
\f1\i0 \
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Good evening.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Christine!\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 You here, so late, Mrs Linde?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Yes, you must excuse me; I was so anxious to see Nora in her dress.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Have you been sitting here waiting for me?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Yes, unfortunately I came too late, you had already gone upstairs; and I thought I couldn\'92t go away again without having seen you.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [taking off NORA\'92S shawl]
\f1\i0 . Yes, take a good look at her. I think she is worth looking at. Isn\'92t she charming, Mrs Linde?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Yes, indeed she is.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Doesn\'92t she look remarkably pretty? Everyone thought so at the dance. But she is terribly self-willed, this sweet little person. What are we to do with her? You will hardly believe that I had almost to bring her away by force.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Torvald, you will repent not having let me stay, even if it were only for half an hour.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Listen to her, Mrs Linde! She had danced her Tarantella, and it had been a tremendous success, as it deserved\'97although possibly the performance was a trifle too realistic\'97a little more so, I mean, than was strictly compatible with the limitations of art. But never mind about that! The chief thing is, she had made a success\'97she had made a tremendous success. Do you think I was going to let her remain there after that, and spoil the effect? No, indeed! I took my charming little Capri maiden\'97my capricious little Capri maiden, I should say\'97on my arm; took one quick turn round the room; a curtsey on either side, and, as they say in novels, the beautiful apparition disappeared. An exit ought always to be effective, Mrs Linde; but that is what I cannot make Nora understand. Pooh! this room is hot. 
\f0\i [Throws his domino on a chair, and opens the door of his room.]
\f1\i0  Hullo! it\'92s all dark in here. Oh, of course\'97excuse me\'97. 
\f0\i [He goes in, and lights some candles.]
\f1\i0 \
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [in a hurried and breathless whisper]
\f1\i0 . Well?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [in a low voice]
\f1\i0 . I have had a talk with him.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, and\'97\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Nora, you must tell your husband all about it.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [in an expressionless voice]
\f1\i0 . I knew it.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 You have nothing to be afraid of as far as Krogstad is concerned; but you must tell him.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I won\'92t tell him.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Then the letter will.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Thank you, Christine. Now I know what I must do. Hush\'97!\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [coming in again]
\f1\i0 . Well, Mrs Linde, have you admired her?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Yes, and now I will say goodnight.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 What, already? Is this yours, this knitting?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [taking it]
\f1\i0 . Yes, thank you, I had very nearly forgotten it.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 So you knit?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Of course.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Do you know, you ought to embroider.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Really? Why?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Yes, it\'92s far more becoming. Let me show you. You hold the embroidery thus in your left hand, and use the needle with the right\'97like this\'97with a long, easy sweep. Do you see?\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Yes, perhaps\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 But in the case of knitting\'97that can never be anything but ungraceful; look here\'97the arms close together, the knitting-needles going up and down\'97it has a sort of Chinese effect\'97. That was really excellent champagne they gave us.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Well,\'97goodnight, Nora, and don\'92t be self-willed any more.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 That\'92s right, Mrs Linde.\
MRS LINDE.\uc0\u8232 Goodnight, Mr. Helmer.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [accompanying her to the door]
\f1\i0 . Goodnight, goodnight. I hope you will get home all right. I should be very happy to\'97but you haven\'92t any great distance to go. Goodnight, goodnight. 
\f0\i [She goes out; he shuts the door after her, and comes in again.]
\f1\i0  Ah!\'97at last we have got rid of her. She is a frightful bore, that woman.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Aren\'92t you very tired, Torvald?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 No, not in the least.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Nor sleepy?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Not a bit. On the contrary, I feel extraordinarily lively. And you?\'97you really look both tired and sleepy.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, I am very tired. I want to go to sleep at once.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 There, you see it was quite right of me not to let you stay there any longer.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Everything you do is quite right, Torvald.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [kissing her on the forehead]
\f1\i0 . Now my little skylark is speaking reasonably. Did you notice what good spirits Rank was in this evening?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Really? Was he? I didn\'92t speak to him at all.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 And I very little, but I have not for a long time seen him in such good form. 
\f0\i [Looks for a while at her and then goes nearer to her.]
\f1\i0  It is delightful to be at home by ourselves again, to be all alone with you\'97you fascinating, charming little darling!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Don\'92t look at me like that, Torvald.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Why shouldn\'92t I look at my dearest treasure?\'97at all the beauty that is mine, all my very own?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [going to the other side of the table]
\f1\i0 . You mustn\'92t say things like that to me tonight.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [following her]
\f1\i0 . You have still got the Tarantella in your blood, I see. And it makes you more captivating than ever. Listen\'97the guests are beginning to go now. 
\f0\i [In a lower voice.]
\f1\i0  Nora\'97soon the whole house will be quiet.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, I hope so.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Yes, my own darling Nora. Do you know, when I am out at a party with you like this, why I speak so little to you, keep away from you, and only send a stolen glance in your direction now and then?\'97do you know why I do that? It is because I make believe to myself that we are secretly in love, and you are my secretly promised bride, and that no one suspects there is anything between us.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, yes\'97I know very well your thoughts are with me all the time.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 And when we are leaving, and I am putting the shawl over your beautiful young shoulders\'97on your lovely neck\'97then I imagine that you are my young bride and that we have just come from the wedding, and I am bringing you for the first time into our home\'97to be alone with you for the first time\'97quite alone with my shy little darling! All this evening I have longed for nothing but you. When I watched the seductive figures of the Tarantella, my blood was on fire; I could endure it no longer, and that was why I brought you down so early\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Go away, Torvald! You must let me go. I won\'92t\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 What\'92s that? You\'92re joking, my little Nora! You won\'92t\'97you won\'92t? Am I not your husband\'97? 
\f0\i [A knock is heard at the outer door.]
\f1\i0 \
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [starting]
\f1\i0 . Did you hear\'97?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [going into the hall]
\f1\i0 . Who is it?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [outside]
\f1\i0 . It is I. May I come in for a moment?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [in a fretful whisper]
\f1\i0 . Oh, what does he want now? 
\f0\i [Aloud.]
\f1\i0  Wait a minute! 
\f0\i [Unlocks the door.]
\f1\i0  Come, that\'92s kind of you not to pass by our door.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 I thought I heard your voice, and felt as if I should like to look in. 
\f0\i [With a swift glance round.]
\f1\i0  Ah, yes!\'97these dear familiar rooms. You are very happy and cosy in here, you two.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 It seems to me that you looked after yourself pretty well upstairs too.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Excellently. Why shouldn\'92t I? Why shouldn\'92t one enjoy everything in this world?\'97at any rate as much as one can, and as long as one can. The wine was capital\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Especially the champagne.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 So you noticed that too? It is almost incredible how much I managed to put away!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Torvald drank a great deal of champagne tonight too.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Did he?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, and he is always in such good spirits afterwards.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Well, why should one not enjoy a merry evening after a well-spent day?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Well spent? I am afraid I can\'92t take credit for that.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [clapping him on the back]
\f1\i0 . But I can, you know!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Doctor Rank, you must have been occupied with some scientific investigation today.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Exactly.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Just listen!\'97little Nora talking about scientific investigations!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 And may I congratulate you on the result?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Indeed you may.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Was it favourable, then?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 The best possible, for both doctor and patient\'97certainty.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [quickly and searchingly]
\f1\i0 . Certainty?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Absolute certainty. So wasn\'92t I entitled to make a merry evening of it after that?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, you certainly were, Doctor Rank.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 I think so too, so long as you don\'92t have to pay for it in the morning.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Oh well, one can\'92t have anything in this life without paying for it.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Doctor Rank\'97are you fond of fancy-dress balls?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Yes, if there is a fine lot of pretty costumes.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Tell me\'97what shall we two wear at the next?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Little featherbrain!\'97are you thinking of the next already?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 We two? Yes, I can tell you. You shall go as a good fairy\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Yes, but what do you suggest as an appropriate costume for that?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Let your wife go dressed just as she is in everyday life.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 That was really very prettily turned. But can\'92t you tell us what you will be?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Yes, my dear friend, I have quite made up my mind about that.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Well?\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 At the next fancy-dress ball I shall be invisible.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 That\'92s a good joke!\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 There is a big black hat\'97have you never heard of hats that make you invisible? If you put one on, no one can see you.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [suppressing a smile]
\f1\i0 . Yes, you are quite right.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 But I am clean forgetting what I came for. Helmer, give me a cigar\'97one of the dark Havanas.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 With the greatest pleasure. 
\f0\i [Offers him his case.]
\f1\i0 \
RANK.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [takes a cigar and cuts off the end]
\f1\i0 . Thanks.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [striking a match]
\f1\i0 . Let me give you a light.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Thank you. 
\f0\i [She holds the match for him to light his cigar.]
\f1\i0  And now goodbye!\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Goodbye, goodbye, dear old man!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Sleep well, Doctor Rank.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 Thank you for that wish.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Wish me the same.\
RANK.\uc0\u8232 You? Well, if you want me to sleep well! And thanks for the light. 
\f0\i [He nods to them both and goes out.]
\f1\i0 \
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [in a subdued voice]
\f1\i0 . He has drunk more than he ought.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [absently]
\f1\i0 . Maybe. 
\f0\i [HELMER takes a bunch of keys out of his pocket and goes into the hall.]
\f1\i0  Torvald! what are you going to do there?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Emptying the letter-box; it is quite full; there will be no room to put the newspaper in tomorrow morning.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Are you going to work tonight?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 You know quite well I\'92m not. What is this? Someone has been at the lock.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 At the lock\'97?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Yes, someone has. What can it mean? I should never have thought the maid\'97. Here is a broken hairpin. Nora, it is one of yours.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [quickly]
\f1\i0 . Then it must have been the children\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Then you must get them out of those ways. There, at last I have got it open. 
\f0\i [Takes out the contents of the letter-box, and calls to the kitchen.]
\f1\i0  Helen!\'97Helen, put out the light over the front door. 
\f0\i [Goes back into the room and shuts the door into the hall. He holds out his hand full of letters.]
\f1\i0  Look at that\'97look what a heap of them there are. 
\f0\i [Turning them over.]
\f1\i0  What on earth is that?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [at the window]
\f1\i0 . The letter\'97No! Torvald, no!\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Two cards\'97of Rank\'92s.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Of Doctor Rank\'92s?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [looking at them]
\f1\i0 . Doctor Rank. They were on the top. He must have put them in when he went out.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Is there anything written on them?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 There is a black cross over the name. Look there\'97what an uncomfortable idea! It looks as if he were announcing his own death.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 It is just what he is doing.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 What? Do you know anything about it? Has he said anything to you?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes. He told me that when the cards came it would be his leave-taking from us. He means to shut himself up and die.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 My poor old friend! Certainly I knew we should not have him very long with us. But so soon! And so he hides himself away like a wounded animal.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 If it has to happen, it is best it should be without a word\'97don\'92t you think so, Torvald?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [walking up and down]
\f1\i0 . He had so grown into our lives. I can\'92t think of him as having gone out of them. He, with his sufferings and his loneliness, was like a cloudy background to our sunlit happiness. Well, perhaps it is best so. For him, anyway. 
\f0\i [Standing still.]
\f1\i0  And perhaps for us too, Nora. We two are thrown quite upon each other now. 
\f0\i [Puts his arms round her.]
\f1\i0  My darling wife, I don\'92t feel as if I could hold you tight enough. Do you know, Nora, I have often wished that you might be threatened by some great danger, so that I might risk my life\'92s blood, and everything, for your sake.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [disengages herself, and says firmly and decidedly]
\f1\i0 . Now you must read your letters, Torvald.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 No, no; not tonight. I want to be with you, my darling wife.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 With the thought of your friend\'92s death\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 You are right, it has affected us both. Something ugly has come between us\'97the thought of the horrors of death. We must try and rid our minds of that. Until then\'97we will each go to our own room.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [hanging on his neck]
\f1\i0 . Goodnight, Torvald\'97Goodnight!\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [kissing her on the forehead]
\f1\i0 . Goodnight, my little singing-bird. Sleep sound, Nora. Now I will read my letters through. 
\f0\i [He takes his letters and goes into his room, shutting the door after him.]
\f1\i0 \
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [gropes distractedly about, seizes HELMER\'92S domino, throws it round her, while she says in quick, hoarse, spasmodic whispers]
\f1\i0 . Never to see him again. Never! Never! 
\f0\i [Puts her shawl over her head.]
\f1\i0  Never to see my children again either\'97never again. Never! Never!\'97Ah! the icy, black water\'97the unfathomable depths\'97If only it were over! He has got it now\'97now he is reading it. Goodbye, Torvald and my children! 
\f0\i [She is about to rush out through the hall, when HELMER opens his door hurriedly and stands with an open letter in his hand.]
\f1\i0 \
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Nora!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Ah!\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 What is this? Do you know what is in this letter?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, I know. Let me go! Let me get out!\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [holding her back]
\f1\i0 . Where are you going?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [trying to get free]
\f1\i0 . You shan\'92t save me, Torvald!\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [reeling]
\f1\i0 . True? Is this true, that I read here? Horrible! No, no\'97it is impossible that it can be true.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 It is true. I have loved you above everything else in the world.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Oh, don\'92t let us have any silly excuses.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [taking a step towards him]
\f1\i0 . Torvald\'97!\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Miserable creature\'97what have you done?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Let me go. You shall not suffer for my sake. You shall not take it upon yourself.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 No tragic airs, please. 
\f0\i [Locks the hall door.]
\f1\i0  Here you shall stay and give me an explanation. Do you understand what you have done? Answer me! Do you understand what you have done?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [looks steadily at him and says with a growing look of coldness in her face]
\f1\i0 . Yes, now I am beginning to understand thoroughly.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [walking about the room]
\f1\i0 . What a horrible awakening! All these eight years\'97she who was my joy and pride\'97a hypocrite, a liar\'97worse, worse\'97a criminal! The unutterable ugliness of it all!\'97For shame! For shame! 
\f0\i [NORA is silent and looks steadily at him. He stops in front of her.]
\f1\i0  I ought to have suspected that something of the sort would happen. I ought to have foreseen it. All your father\'92s want of principle\'97be silent!\'97all your father\'92s want of principle has come out in you. No religion, no morality, no sense of duty\'97. How I am punished for having winked at what he did! I did it for your sake, and this is how you repay me.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, that\'92s just it.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Now you have destroyed all my happiness. You have ruined all my future. It is horrible to think of! I am in the power of an unscrupulous man; he can do what he likes with me, ask anything he likes of me, give me any orders he pleases\'97I dare not refuse. And I must sink to such miserable depths because of a thoughtless woman!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 When I am out of the way, you will be free.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 No fine speeches, please. Your father had always plenty of those ready, too. What good would it be to me if you were out of the way, as you say? Not the slightest. He can make the affair known everywhere; and if he does, I may be falsely suspected of having been a party to your criminal action. Very likely people will think I was behind it all\'97that it was I who prompted you! And I have to thank you for all this\'97you whom I have cherished during the whole of our married life. Do you understand now what it is you have done for me?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [coldly and quietly]
\f1\i0 . Yes.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 It is so incredible that I can\'92t take it in. But we must come to some understanding. Take off that shawl. Take it off, I tell you. I must try and appease him some way or another. The matter must be hushed up at any cost. And as for you and me, it must appear as if everything between us were just as before\'97but naturally only in the eyes of the world. You will still remain in my house, that is a matter of course. But I shall not allow you to bring up the children; I dare not trust them to you. To think that I should be obliged to say so to one whom I have loved so dearly, and whom I still\'97. No, that is all over. From this moment happiness is not the question; all that concerns us is to save the remains, the fragments, the appearance\'97\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi320\sa80\qj\partightenfactor0

\f0\i \cf0 [A ring is heard at the front-door bell.]
\f1\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [with a start]
\f1\i0 . What is that? So late! Can the worst\'97? Can he\'97? Hide yourself, Nora. Say you are ill.\
\pard\pardeftab720\fi320\sa80\qj\partightenfactor0

\f0\i \cf0 [NORA stands motionless. HELMER goes and unlocks the hall door.]
\f1\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qj\partightenfactor0
\cf0 MAID.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [half-dressed, comes to the door]
\f1\i0 . A letter for the mistress.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Give it to me. 
\f0\i [Takes the letter, and shuts the door.]
\f1\i0  Yes, it is from him. You shall not have it; I will read it myself.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, read it.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [standing by the lamp]
\f1\i0 . I scarcely have the courage to do it. It may mean ruin for both of us. No, I must know. 
\f0\i [Tears open the letter, runs his eye over a few lines, looks at a paper enclosed, and gives a shout of joy.]
\f1\i0  Nora! 
\f0\i [She looks at him questioningly.]
\f1\i0  Nora!\'97No, I must read it once again\'97. Yes, it is true! I am saved! Nora, I am saved!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 And I?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 You too, of course; we are both saved, both you and I. Look, he sends you your bond back. He says he regrets and repents\'97that a happy change in his life\'97never mind what he says! We are saved, Nora! No one can do anything to you. Oh, Nora, Nora!\'97no, first I must destroy these hateful things. Let me see\'97. 
\f0\i [Takes a look at the bond.]
\f1\i0  No, no, I won\'92t look at it. The whole thing shall be nothing but a bad dream to me. 
\f0\i [Tears up the bond and both letters, throws them all into the stove, and watches them burn.]
\f1\i0  There\'97now it doesn\'92t exist any longer. He says that since Christmas Eve you\'97. These must have been three dreadful days for you, Nora.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I have fought a hard fight these three days.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 And suffered agonies, and seen no way out but\'97. No, we won\'92t call any of the horrors to mind. We will only shout with joy, and keep saying, \'93It\'92s all over! It\'92s all over!\'94 Listen to me, Nora. You don\'92t seem to realise that it is all over. What is this?\'97such a cold, set face! My poor little Nora, I quite understand; you don\'92t feel as if you could believe that I have forgiven you. But it is true, Nora, I swear it; I have forgiven you everything. I know that what you did, you did out of love for me.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 That is true.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 You have loved me as a wife ought to love her husband. Only you had not sufficient knowledge to judge of the means you used. But do you suppose you are any the less dear to me, because you don\'92t understand how to act on your own responsibility? No, no; only lean on me; I will advise you and direct you. I should not be a man if this womanly helplessness did not just give you a double attractiveness in my eyes. You must not think anymore about the hard things I said in my first moment of consternation, when I thought everything was going to overwhelm me. I have forgiven you, Nora; I swear to you I have forgiven you.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Thank you for your forgiveness. 
\f0\i [She goes out through the door to the right.]
\f1\i0 \
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 No, don\'92t go\'97. 
\f0\i [Looks in.]
\f1\i0  What are you doing in there?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [from within]
\f1\i0 . Taking off my fancy dress.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [standing at the open door]
\f1\i0 . Yes, do. Try and calm yourself, and make your mind easy again, my frightened little singing-bird. Be at rest, and feel secure; I have broad wings to shelter you under. 
\f0\i [Walks up and down by the door.]
\f1\i0  How warm and cosy our home is, Nora. Here is shelter for you; here I will protect you like a hunted dove that I have saved from a hawk\'92s claws; I will bring peace to your poor beating heart. It will come, little by little, Nora, believe me. Tomorrow morning you will look upon it all quite differently; soon everything will be just as it was before. Very soon you won\'92t need me to assure you that I have forgiven you; you will yourself feel the certainty that I have done so. Can you suppose I should ever think of such a thing as repudiating you, or even reproaching you? You have no idea what a true man\'92s heart is like, Nora. There is something so indescribably sweet and satisfying, to a man, in the knowledge that he has forgiven his wife\'97forgiven her freely, and with all his heart. It seems as if that had made her, as it were, doubly his own; he has given her a new life, so to speak; and she has in a way become both wife and child to him. So you shall be for me after this, my little scared, helpless darling. Have no anxiety about anything, Nora; only be frank and open with me, and I will serve as will and conscience both to you\'97. What is this? Not gone to bed? Have you changed your things?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [in everyday dress]
\f1\i0 . Yes, Torvald, I have changed my things now.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 But what for?\'97so late as this.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I shall not sleep tonight.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 But, my dear Nora\'97\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [looking at her watch]
\f1\i0 . It is not so very late. Sit down here, Torvald. You and I have much to say to one another. 
\f0\i [She sits down at one side of the table.]
\f1\i0 \
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Nora\'97what is this?\'97this cold, set face?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Sit down. It will take some time; I have a lot to talk over with you.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [sits down at the opposite side of the table]
\f1\i0 . You alarm me, Nora!\'97and I don\'92t understand you.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, that is just it. You don\'92t understand me, and I have never understood you either\'97before tonight. No, you mustn\'92t interrupt me. You must simply listen to what I say. Torvald, this is a settling of accounts.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 What do you mean by that?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [after a short silence]
\f1\i0 . Isn\'92t there one thing that strikes you as strange in our sitting here like this?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 What is that?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 We have been married now eight years. Does it not occur to you that this is the first time we two, you and I, husband and wife, have had a serious conversation?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 What do you mean by serious?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 In all these eight years\'97longer than that\'97from the very beginning of our acquaintance, we have never exchanged a word on any serious subject.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Was it likely that I would be continually and forever telling you about worries that you could not help me to bear?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I am not speaking about business matters. I say that we have never sat down in earnest together to try and get at the bottom of anything.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 But, dearest Nora, would it have been any good to you?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 That is just it; you have never understood me. I have been greatly wronged, Torvald\'97first by papa and then by you.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 What! By us two\'97by us two, who have loved you better than anyone else in the world?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [shaking her head]
\f1\i0 . You have never loved me. You have only thought it pleasant to be in love with me.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Nora, what do I hear you saying?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 It is perfectly true, Torvald. When I was at home with papa, he told me his opinion about everything, and so I had the same opinions; and if I differed from him I concealed the fact, because he would not have liked it. He called me his doll-child, and he played with me just as I used to play with my dolls. And when I came to live with you\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 What sort of an expression is that to use about our marriage?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [undisturbed]
\f1\i0 . I mean that I was simply transferred from papa\'92s hands into yours. You arranged everything according to your own taste, and so I got the same tastes as you\'97or else I pretended to, I am really not quite sure which\'97I think sometimes the one and sometimes the other. When I look back on it, it seems to me as if I had been living here like a poor woman\'97just from hand to mouth. I have existed merely to perform tricks for you, Torvald. But you would have it so. You and papa have committed a great sin against me. It is your fault that I have made nothing of my life.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 How unreasonable and how ungrateful you are, Nora! Have you not been happy here?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, I have never been happy. I thought I was, but it has never really been so.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Not\'97not happy!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, only merry. And you have always been so kind to me. But our home has been nothing but a playroom. I have been your doll-wife, just as at home I was papa\'92s doll-child; and here the children have been my dolls. I thought it great fun when you played with me, just as they thought it great fun when I played with them. That is what our marriage has been, Torvald.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 There is some truth in what you say\'97exaggerated and strained as your view of it is. But for the future it shall be different. Playtime shall be over, and lesson-time shall begin.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Whose lessons? Mine, or the children\'92s?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Both yours and the children\'92s, my darling Nora.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Alas, Torvald, you are not the man to educate me into being a proper wife for you.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 And you can say that!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 And I\'97how am I fitted to bring up the children?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Nora!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Didn\'92t you say so yourself a little while ago\'97that you dare not trust me to bring them up?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 In a moment of anger! Why do you pay any heed to that?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Indeed, you were perfectly right. I am not fit for the task. There is another task I must undertake first. I must try and educate myself\'97you are not the man to help me in that. I must do that for myself. And that is why I am going to leave you now.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [springing up]
\f1\i0 . What do you say?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I must stand quite alone, if I am to understand myself and everything about me. It is for that reason that I cannot remain with you any longer.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Nora, Nora!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I am going away from here now, at once. I am sure Christine will take me in for the night\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 You are out of your mind! I won\'92t allow it! I forbid you!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 It is no use forbidding me anything any longer. I will take with me what belongs to myself. I will take nothing from you, either now or later.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 What sort of madness is this!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Tomorrow I shall go home\'97I mean, to my old home. It will be easiest for me to find something to do there.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 You blind, foolish woman!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I must try and get some sense, Torvald.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 To desert your home, your husband and your children! And you don\'92t consider what people will say!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I cannot consider that at all. I only know that it is necessary for me.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 It\'92s shocking. This is how you would neglect your most sacred duties.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 What do you consider my most sacred duties?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Do I need to tell you that? Are they not your duties to your husband and your children?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I have other duties just as sacred.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 That you have not. What duties could those be?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Duties to myself.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Before all else, you are a wife and a mother.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I don\'92t believe that any longer. I believe that before all else I am a reasonable human being, just as you are\'97or, at all events, that I must try and become one. I know quite well, Torvald, that most people would think you right, and that views of that kind are to be found in books; but I can no longer content myself with what most people say, or with what is found in books. I must think over things for myself and get to understand them.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Can you not understand your place in your own home? Have you not a reliable guide in such matters as that?\'97have you no religion?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I am afraid, Torvald, I do not exactly know what religion is.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 What are you saying?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I know nothing but what the clergyman said, when I went to be confirmed. He told us that religion was this, and that, and the other. When I am away from all this, and am alone, I will look into that matter too. I will see if what the clergyman said is true, or at all events if it is true for me.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 This is unheard of in a girl of your age! But if religion cannot lead you aright, let me try and awaken your conscience. I suppose you have some moral sense? Or\'97answer me\'97am I to think you have none?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I assure you, Torvald, that is not an easy question to answer. I really don\'92t know. The thing perplexes me altogether. I only know that you and I look at it in quite a different light. I am learning, too, that the law is quite another thing from what I supposed; but I find it impossible to convince myself that the law is right. According to it a woman has no right to spare her old dying father, or to save her husband\'92s life. I can\'92t believe that.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 You talk like a child. You don\'92t understand the conditions of the world in which you live.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, I don\'92t. But now I am going to try. I am going to see if I can make out who is right, the world or I.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 You are ill, Nora; you are delirious; I almost think you are out of your mind.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I have never felt my mind so clear and certain as tonight.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 And is it with a clear and certain mind that you forsake your husband and your children?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, it is.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Then there is only one possible explanation.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 What is that?\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 You do not love me anymore.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 No, that is just it.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Nora!\'97and you can say that?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 It gives me great pain, Torvald, for you have always been so kind to me, but I cannot help it. I do not love you any more.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [regaining his composure]
\f1\i0 . Is that a clear and certain conviction too?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, absolutely clear and certain. That is the reason why I will not stay here any longer.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 And can you tell me what I have done to forfeit your love?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Yes, indeed I can. It was tonight, when the wonderful thing did not happen; then I saw you were not the man I had thought you were.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Explain yourself better. I don\'92t understand you.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 I have waited so patiently for eight years; for, goodness knows, I knew very well that wonderful things don\'92t happen every day. Then this horrible misfortune came upon me; and then I felt quite certain that the wonderful thing was going to happen at last. When Krogstad\'92s letter was lying out there, never for a moment did I imagine that you would consent to accept this man\'92s conditions. I was so absolutely certain that you would say to him: Publish the thing to the whole world. And when that was done\'97\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Yes, what then?\'97when I had exposed my wife to shame and disgrace?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 When that was done, I was so absolutely certain, you would come forward and take everything upon yourself, and say: I am the guilty one.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Nora\'97!\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 You mean that I would never have accepted such a sacrifice on your part? No, of course not. But what would my assurances have been worth against yours? That was the wonderful thing which I hoped for and feared; and it was to prevent that, that I wanted to kill myself.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 I would gladly work night and day for you, Nora\'97bear sorrow and want for your sake. But no man would sacrifice his honour for the one he loves.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 It is a thing hundreds of thousands of women have done.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Oh, you think and talk like a heedless child.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Maybe. But you neither think nor talk like the man I could bind myself to. As soon as your fear was over\'97and it was not fear for what threatened me, but for what might happen to you\'97when the whole thing was past, as far as you were concerned it was exactly as if nothing at all had happened. Exactly as before, I was your little skylark, your doll, which you would in future treat with doubly gentle care, because it was so brittle and fragile. 
\f0\i [Getting up.]
\f1\i0  Torvald\'97it was then it dawned upon me that for eight years I had been living here with a strange man, and had borne him three children\'97. Oh, I can\'92t bear to think of it! I could tear myself into little bits!\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [sadly]
\f1\i0 . I see, I see. An abyss has opened between us\'97there is no denying it. But, Nora, would it not be possible to fill it up?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 As I am now, I am no wife for you.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 I have it in me to become a different man.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Perhaps\'97if your doll is taken away from you.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 But to part!\'97to part from you! No, no, Nora, I can\'92t understand that idea.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [going out to the right]
\f1\i0 . That makes it all the more certain that it must be done. 
\f0\i [She comes back with her cloak and hat and a small bag which she puts on a chair by the table.]
\f1\i0 \
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Nora, Nora, not now! Wait until tomorrow.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [putting on her cloak]
\f1\i0 . I cannot spend the night in a strange man\'92s room.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 But can\'92t we live here like brother and sister\'97?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 
\f0\i [putting on her hat]
\f1\i0 . You know very well that would not last long. 
\f0\i [Puts the shawl round her.]
\f1\i0  Goodbye, Torvald. I won\'92t see the little ones. I know they are in better hands than mine. As I am now, I can be of no use to them.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 But some day, Nora\'97some day?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 How can I tell? I have no idea what is going to become of me.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 But you are my wife, whatever becomes of you.\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 Listen, Torvald. I have heard that when a wife deserts her husband\'92s house, as I am doing now, he is legally freed from all obligations towards her. In any case, I set you free from all your obligations. You are not to feel yourself bound in the slightest way, any more than I shall. There must be perfect freedom on both sides. See, here is your ring back. Give me mine.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 That too?\
NORA.\uc0\u8232 That too.\
HELMER.\uc0\u8232 Here it is.\
